# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# jiff-cli is the **development CLI for the jiff
# datetime library** from BurntSushi (the ripgrep / regex
# / aho-corasick / xsv author).  Pivots from pico_args
# (R274 koto) into the **lexopt token-level Rust CLI
# cluster**.  Sister to ripgrep / regex / xsv (all
# BurntSushi).  **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's **first
# documented lexopt Rust CLI** — adds a 6TH variant to
# the Rust CLI library taxonomy.
#
# Critical extraction note: jiff-cli uses **`lexopt`**
# library at `lexopt::Parser::from_env()` — corpus's
# **first documented `lexopt` Rust CLI**.  lexopt is
# a **token-level CLI parser** — even lower-level than
# pico_args (R274 koto).  lexopt gives you raw Arg
# tokens (`Arg::Short(c)`, `Arg::Long(name)`,
# `Arg::Value(v)`) and you build the entire parser
# yourself.  No flag declarations, no auto-help, no
# value parsing.  You write a `while let Some(arg) =
# p.next()? { match arg { ... } }` loop and dispatch
# manually.  Documents the **token-level CLI parser
# pattern** — between hand-rolled (R273 irust) and
# pico_args (R274 koto) in abstraction.  Extends the
# Rust CLI library sub-taxonomy to SIX variants (R273
# added hand-rolled; R274 added pico_args; R275 adds
# lexopt): (a) clap derive, (b) clap builder, (c) clap
# v3, (d) hand-rolled (R273), (e) pico_args (R274),
# (f) **lexopt** (R275 — NEW).  lexopt is used by
# nushell, RustPython, regex, newsboat, ocrs, jiff —
# all serious Rust tools where the developer wants
# **fine-grained control** over arg parsing without
# clap's compile-time cost.
#
# Critical extraction note: jiff-cli uses **enum-based
# Arg representation** at args/mod.rs:21-58 — lexopt's
# `Arg` enum has variants `Short(char)`, `Long(&str)`,
# `Value(OsString)`.  The parsing loop matches on
# these via `match arg { Arg::Short('h') | Arg::Long
# ("help") => ... }`.  Documents the **lexopt Arg-
# variant matching pattern** — distinct from
# pico_args's high-level `args.contains([short, long])`
# (R274 koto) and from clap's struct-attribute
# decorators.  lexopt's approach is closer to writing
# a parser by hand but with a tokenizer doing the dirty
# work.
#
# Critical extraction note: jiff-cli uses **`Configurable`
# trait pattern** at args/mod.rs:5-13 — a custom trait
# defining `configure(&mut self, p: &mut Parser, arg:
# &mut Arg) -> Result<bool>` + `usage() -> &[Usage]`.
# Each subcommand defines its own struct that
# implements Configurable.  The central `configure`
# fn at args/mod.rs:15-72 takes `&mut [&mut dyn
# Configurable]` and iterates through ALL targets for
# each parsed arg, asking each "do you want this?".
# First target to claim the arg wins.  Documents the
# **distributed-trait-dispatch arg-handler pattern**
# — corpus's first.  Useful when subcommand args are
# spread across modules and you want each module to
# own its arg handling.  Distinct from clap derive's
# centralized struct (which collects all args into
# one struct) and from pico_args's procedural style
# (which queries the parser linearly).
#
# Critical extraction note: jiff-cli uses **manual
# Usage struct + Usage::short/long formatters** at
# args/mod.rs:121-193 — a custom struct
# `Usage { format: &'static str, short: &'static str,
# long: &'static str }` representing per-flag help
# text.  `Usage::short(&[Usage])` formats a two-column
# table (format | short description); `Usage::long(...)`
# formats with multi-paragraph long descriptions
# wrapped at 79 columns via `textwrap::wrap`.  The
# `-h` flag triggers short help; `--help` triggers
# long help.  Documents the **manual help-formatting
# infrastructure** pattern — lexopt has NO auto-help
# generation, so you build your own.  Distinct from
# R266 uvicorn's Click `show_default=True`
# (auto-included) and from R262 matugen's clap
# `help = "..."` per-arg (auto-rendered).  Plus jiff-
# cli's `-h` vs `--help` distinction — `-h` is short,
# `--help` is long.  Corpus's **first documented `-h`
# vs `--help` (length-based) distinction**.  Documents
# the **2 help-flag formats** (length-based vs same-
# format).
#
# Critical extraction note: jiff-cli uses **manual
# USAGE string at each level** at cmd/mod.rs:3-11 +
# cmd/generate/mod.rs:13-26 — each subcommand has its
# own USAGE constant printed via `anyhow::bail!(USAGE)`.
# When `-h` or `--help` is given at any level, the
# subcommand's USAGE is printed and the program exits
# with an error.  Documents the **per-subcommand USAGE
# constant pattern** — distinct from clap derive's
# auto-generated help (which composes from doc
# comments) and from Cmdliner's man-page sections
# (R271 dune).

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1

# Single top-level subcommand: `generate`.
local -a subcommands=(
  'generate:various generation tasks for jiff-tzdb and related (sub: crc32 / jiff-tzdb / shared / unit-designator-match / windows-zones / zoneinfo)'
)

# 6 generate sub-subcommands at cmd/generate/mod.rs:30-37.
local -a generate_subs=(
  'crc32:generate CRC32 data tables'
  'jiff-tzdb:generate Rust source code from TZif data for jiff-tzdb'
  'shared:copy shared code from Jiff to jiff-static proc macro'
  'unit-designator-match:generate Rust `match` expression for parsing unit labels'
  'windows-zones:generate mapping Windows TZ names to IANA names'
  'zoneinfo:generate TZif data for jiff-tzdb'
)

_arguments -C \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help (-h = short table; --help = long descriptions)]' \
  '1:subcommand:->subcmd' \
  '*::args:->args' && ret=0

case $state in
  subcmd)
    _describe -t subcommands 'jiff-cli subcommand' subcommands && ret=0
    ;;
  args)
    case $words[1] in
      generate)
        if (( CURRENT == 2 )); then
          _describe -t generate-subs 'generate kind' generate_subs && ret=0
        else
          # Each sub-subcommand has its own args.  Without
          # full extraction here we fall back to files.
          _files && ret=0
        fi
        ;;
    esac
    ;;
esac

return ret
